# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alan-trammell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] The **1976 Major League Baseball draft** took place prior to the 1976 MLB season.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] The draft saw the Houston Astros select Floyd Bannister first overall.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] The following are the first-round picks in the 1976 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] The 1976 Arizona State University team, considered by many to be the best collegiate team ever, played a major role in the draft.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] Floyd Bannister was picked number one by the Astros while Ken Landreaux was selected sixth by the Angels.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] In all, 12 players from that team went on to play in the majors.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] Bannister and Landreaux anchored a June draft that was one of the most talented ever.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] The first 10 selections went on to play in the big leagues.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] Among those picked in the June draft were Rickey Henderson (Oakland), Alan Trammell, Jack Morris and Dan Petry (Detroit), Wade Boggs and Bruce Hurst (Boston), Steve Trout (Chicago White Sox), Leon Durham (St.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] Louis), and Pat Tabler (New York Yankees).
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] Willie McGee (Chicago White Sox) and Ozzie Smith (Detroit) were selected in the seventh round but did not sign.
[src:alan-trammell/1976-mlb-draft] In the January phase, Steve Kemp of Southern California was picked first by the Tigers and Jody Davis was picked third by the Mets.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] The **1977 Detroit Tigers season** was the team's 77th season and the 66th season at Tiger Stadium.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place in the American League East with a record of 74–88, 26 games behind the New York Yankees.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] They were outscored by their opponents 751 to 714.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers drew 1,359,856 fans to Tiger Stadium in 1977, ranking 7th of the 14 teams in the American League.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] With 212 hits, 100 runs scored, and a .325 batting average, center fielder Ron LeFlore was the team's most valuable player, and the recipient of the "Tiger of the Year" award.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman Jason Thompson led the team with 31 home runs and 105 RBIs, and second baseman Tito Fuentes was the team's only other .300 hitter, with a .309 batting average and 190 hits.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] Designated hitter Rusty Staub also had a .278 batting average, 173 hits, 22 home runs, and 101 RBIs.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] Rookie Steve Kemp (the first pick in the 1976 amateur draft) hit .257 with 18 home runs and 88 RBIs.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] The rookie sensation of 1976, Mark Fidrych pitched in 1977 (2.89 ERA), but tendinitis limited "The Bird" to 11 games.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] The pitching star of 1977 for Detroit was rookie Dave Rozema who went 15–7 with a 3.09 ERA and finished eighth in the American League Cy Young Award voting.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-detroit-tigers-season] 1977 also saw the debut of Steve Kemp (debut April 7, 1977), Dave Rozema (debut April 11, 1977), Jack Morris (debut July 26, 1977), Lance Parrish (debut September 5, 1977), Alan Trammell (debut September 9, 1977), and Lou Whitaker (debut September 9, 1977).
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The **1977 major league baseball season** began on April 6 while the regular season ended on October 2.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Cincinnati Reds from the 1976 season.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The 48th All-Star Game was held on July 13 at Yankee Stadium in New York, New York, home of the New York Yankees.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The National League won, 7–5, and was the sixth win in what would be a 10-win streak that lasted until 1983.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The season saw the fourth round of expansion (and third for the American League) since the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] While the National League voted at the same time as the American League to expand over the 1976 off-season, the National League did not have the necessary unanimous results to expand.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The league would not expand to 14 teams until 1993 when the Colorado Rockies and Florida Marlins were enfranchised.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The 1977 schedule consisted of 162 games for all 14 teams in the American League and 12 teams in the National League.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] For the first time since 1961, the two leagues saw different schedule formats.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The American League was split into two seven-team divisions.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 15 games against their six division rivals, totaling 90 games, and 10 games against five opponents and 11 games against two opponents, totaling 72 interdivision games.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League was split into two six-team divisions.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against their five division rivals, totaling 90 games, and 12 games against six interdivision opponents, totaling 72 games.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1969 and would continue to be the format in use until 1993.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 6, featuring four teams.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2, featuring all 26 teams.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The National League Championship Series took place between October 4 and October 8, while the American League Championship Series took place between October 5 and October 9.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 11 and October 18.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 18 with the New York Yankees defeating the Los Angeles Dodgers in the 1977 World Series in six games.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The Montreal Expos leave Jarry Park Stadium (where they played for eight seasons) and opened Olympic Stadium, where they would go on to play for 28 seasons through 2004.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] ABC aired *Monday Night Baseball* and the World Series.
[src:alan-trammell/1977-major-league-baseball-season] NBC televised the weekend *Game of the Week*, the All-Star Game, and both League Championship Series.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1980 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 51st midseason exhibition between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and the National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was played on July 8, 1980, at Dodger Stadium in Los Angeles, California, home of the Los Angeles Dodgers of the National League.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in a 4–2 victory for the NL.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] While this would mark the second time that the Dodgers had hosted the All-Star Game in Los Angeles, it was the first time that the game was being held at Dodger Stadium.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Their first time as host in 1959 saw the game played at Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum; the Dodgers' Los Angeles home field until the construction of Dodger Stadium.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This All-Star Game would be known for some exemplary pitching performances, most notably AL starter Steve Stone's (three perfect innings, three strikeouts).
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Jerry Reuss struck out the side for the NL in the sixth, as well.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It would also be one of the final games for NL starter J.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Richard was diagnosed with a career-ending stroke weeks later.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The pregame ceremonies of the All-Star Game featured Disney characters.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Later, Edwards Air Force Base of Rosamond, California, provided both the colors presentation and, after the Los Angeles All-City Band performed the Canadian and U.S.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] National Anthems, the flyover ceremonies.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This All-Star Game marked the first nationally televised US performance of *O Canada* after it had officially been designated the Canadian National Anthem seven days earlier on July 1, 1980.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It also marked the debut of the modern-day large-scale video screen, with the first such video scoreboard, Diamond Vision by Mitsubishi Electric, being introduced at this game.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL and NL were locked in a scoreless duel for four innings, including Stone's performance mentioned above.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Fred Lynn would break the deadlock in the top of the fifth with a two-run homer off Bob Welch.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The National League came back with a single run in their half of the fifth when Ken Griffey homered off Tommy John.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL took the lead in the bottom of the sixth when George Hendrick singled home Ray Knight and Phil Garner scored on a Willie Randolph error.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL's final run scored in the seventh when Dave Concepcion reached on a fielder's choice, went to second on a wild-pitch by Dave Stieb, then to third on a passed ball by Darrell Porter, and came home on another Stieb wild pitch.
[src:alan-trammell/1980-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The **1984 American League Championship Series** was a semifinal matchup in Major League Baseball's 1984 postseason which matched the East Division champion Detroit Tigers against the West Division champion Kansas City Royals.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The Tigers took the series in a three-game sweep to advance to the 1984 World Series against the San Diego Padres; the Royals never held a lead in any inning of the series.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The sixteenth edition of the ALCS, it was the last to be played as a best-of-five, as both the American League and National League would change their League Championship Series to a best-of-seven format.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The 1984 American League Championship Series ended in a sweep by the Tigers, although Games 2 and 3 were both close.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Game 2 was decided in extra innings, and the Tigers clinched the pennant with a 1–0 victory in Game 3.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Detroit never trailed in the series, and led in 26 of the 29 innings played (with the other three tied).
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The result wasn't that surprising given that the Royals won 20 fewer games during the season and had won the AL West by a mere three games over both the California Angels and Minnesota Twins.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The striking umpires originally scheduled to work the ALCS were Marty Springstead (crew chief), Don Denkinger, Steve Palermo, Ken Kaiser, Greg Kosc and John Shulock (who was not a member of the Major League Umpires Association since he was hired by the AL during the 1979 MLUA strike).
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Game 1 was a blowout in Kansas City, as the Tigers struck first when Lou Whitaker singled to lead off the game off of Bud Black, then scored on Alan Trammell's triple.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] One out later, Lance Parrish's sacrifice fly made it 2–0 Tigers.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Leadoff home runs by Larry Herndon in the fourth and Trammell in the fifth made it 4–0 Tigers.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] In the seventh, Royals' right fielder Pat Sheridan's error on Whitaker's line drive allowed him to reach second, then score on Trammell's single off of Mark Huismann.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Tigers' Jack Morris pitched seven innings, allowing only one run in the seventh when Jorge Orta hit a leadoff triple and scored on Darryl Motley's groundout, with Willie Hernández pitching the final two innings.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The Tigers added to their lead in the last two innings off of the Royals' bullpen.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Barbaro Garbey led off the eighth with a single off of Huismann and scored on Darrell Evans's double, then Marty Castillo's RBI single made it 7–1 Tigers.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Lance Parrish's leadoff home run in the ninth off of Mike Jones capped the scoring at 8–1 as the Tigers took a 1–0 series lead.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The Tigers took Game 2 in extra innings by a 5–3 score.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] In the top of the first, Lou Whitaker reached on an error off of Bret Saberhagen, then back-to-back one-out RBI doubles by Kirk Gibson and Lance Parrish put the Tigers up 2–0.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Gibson's home run in the third made it 3–0 Tigers.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Detroit's "Senor Smoke", Aurelio López, held the Royals scoreless in the ninth, tenth and eleventh innings for the win.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Johnny Grubb hit a double off Dan Quisenberry in the 11th inning to drive in Darrell Evans and Ruppert Jones for the game winning runs.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The first postseason game at Tiger Stadium in 12 years was a pitcher's duel between Milt Wilcox and Charlie Leibrandt.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Leibrandt pitched a complete game, allowing only one run and three hits, while Wilcox gave up two hits and struck out eight Royals with Willie Hernández pitching the ninth inning for the save.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Marty Castillo's 2nd inning groundout to drove in Chet Lemon for game's lone run as the Tigers completed the three-game sweep and advanced to the World Series.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] This was Detroit's first pennant in 16 years and the ninth in the team's history.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Had the ALCS gone the full five games, Game 5 on Sunday October 7, would have been a 1 p.m.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] ET time start instead of being in prime time.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] This would have happened because one of the presidential debates between Ronald Reagan and Walter Mondale was scheduled for that night.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Accordingly, ABC planned to broadcast the debates instead of Game 5 in prime time.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] The Royals would win the World Series the next season in 1985.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] It was seen as the culmination of ten years of dominance by the Royals, during which they reached the playoffs seven times, with stars such as George Brett, Hal McRae and Willie Wilson, but kept coming up just short.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] Unlike the 1976–1984 Royals, who played poorly in elimination games, the 1985 Royals went 6–0 in such games, after falling behind 2–0 and 3–1 and staging comebacks in both the American League Championship Series and World Series.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-american-league-championship-series] In 1998, the Detroit Tigers would move to from the American League East to the American League Central and form a divisional rivalry with the Kansas City Royals.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The **1984 Detroit Tigers season** was the team's 84th season and the 73rd season at Tiger Stadium; the Tigers won the 1984 World Series, defeating the San Diego Padres in five games.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The season was their 84th since they entered the American League in 1901.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] It was the franchise's best season in terms of overall wins (104) and their best win percentage (.642) in a 162-game season.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Tigers led the American League East wire-to-wire, opening the season 9–0 and eventually topping out at 35–5 (.875) after 40 games, with a 17–0 road record.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The team won its first Division title since 1972, their first American League championship since 1968 (ninth overall), and the franchise's fourth (and most recent) World Series.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Detroit relief pitcher Willie Hernández won the Cy Young Award and was chosen as the American League Most Valuable Player.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Catcher Lance Parrish, known as the "Big Wheel", led the team in home runs (33) and RBIs (98) -- and strikeouts (120) as well.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Parrish was the starting catcher for the American League All Star team and won the Gold Glove and Silver Slugger Awards in 1984.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He hit 2 home runs and had 5 RBIs in postseason play.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Dave Bergman was acquired from the Giants (via the Phillies) in March 1984 and became the Tigers' principal first baseman, playing 114 games at the position.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He hit .273 in the regular season, but failed to get a hit in 5 games of the 1984 World Series.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On June 4, 1984, Bergman had an 11th inning at-bat at home in a big game against second-place Toronto, who at that point trailed the Tigers by only five games.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The at-bat lasted 13 pitches (7 minutes), with Bergman fouling off seven straight pitches from Roy Lee Jackson before hitting a walk-off, three-run home run.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Sparky Anderson called it the greatest at-bat he had ever seen.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Second baseman Lou Whitaker, known as "Sweet Lou", had his best year in 1983, hitting .320 with 40 doubles and 206 hits.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Though his batting numbers were much lower in 1984 (.289 average, 25 doubles and 161 hits), he was selected as the starting second baseman for the American League All Star team and won the Gold Glove and Silver Slugger Awards in 1984.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Shortstop Alan Trammell had a big year in 1984.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] His .314 batting average was 5th best in the American League and 25 points higher than any other Tiger.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He was selected for the American League All Star team and won his 4th Gold Glove award at shortstop.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Trammell was also named the Most Valuable Player of the 1984 World Series after batting .450, driving in 6 runs and hitting 2 home runs.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Third base was a weak spot in the Detroit lineup, with light-hitting Tom Brookens entering as the starter from 1980 to 1983.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In 1984, manager Sparky Anderson searched for the right third baseman, as five different players appeared in 19 or more games at the position that season: 108 by Howard Johnson, 68 by Brookens, 33 by Marty Castillo, 20 by Bárbaro Garbey, and 19 by Darrell Evans.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Howard Johnson, nicknamed "HoJo", was the starting third baseman on Opening Day and through most of the 1984 season.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Johnson had a disappointing year, batting .248 with 12 home runs and 50 RBIs.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In the 1984 World Series, Sparky Anderson gave the third base job to Marty Castillo, and HoJo had only 1 pinch-hit at bat.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Johnson was traded to the Mets less than 2 months after the World Series, and went on to have some big years in New York (36 HRs, 101 RBIs in 1989).
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The image of Kirk Gibson with his arms raised above his head after hitting a 3-run home run in the 1984 World Series has become the iconic symbol of the Tigers' 1984 season.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The blast came off Goose Gossage, the best reliever in the National League, in the 8th inning of the 5th and final game.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] It put the Tigers ahead, 8–4, and sealed the championship.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] During the regular season, the Detroit area native played right field and led the team with a .516 slugging percentage.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He also contributed 27 home runs, 91 RBIs and 29 stolen bases, and was #6 in the American League Most Valuable Player voting.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Chet Lemon was the starting center fielder in the 1984 All Star game and a major contributor to the Tigers' success in 1984.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] One of the best defensive outfielders in baseball, Lemon had 427 putouts in 1984 with a .995 fielding percentage; his 3.09 Range factor rating was far above the league average of 2.17.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Lemon also contributed to the team's offensive output with a .287 batting average, 20 home runs, 34 doubles, 76 RBIs, and a.495 slugging percentage.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Larry Herndon played 117 games in left field for the 1984 Tigers and hit .280.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In the World Series, he had a .333 batting average and hit a home run.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] His 2-run homer in Game 1 was the difference in a 3–2 Tigers win.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He also caught the final out of the World Series, a fly ball off the bat of Tony Gwynn.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Jack Morris was the leader of the Tigers pitching staff.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He threw a no-hitter in April and was 10–1 before the end of May.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He was selected for the 1984 All Star team, but finished the season 9–10 from June through September.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He was 19–11 in the regular season with a 3.60 ERA.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He won all three of his post-season starts, tossing two complete games and allowing only five earned runs in 25 innings (1.80 ERA).
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The team's #2 starter, Dan Petry, finished the year 18–8 with the 3rd best winning percentage (.692) in the American League.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] His 3.24 ERA in the regular season was the lowest among the Tiger starters.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The team's #3 starter, Milt Wilcox, was 17–8 with a 4.00 ERA.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Wilcox was 2–0 in the post-season, giving up only 1 run in 14 innings.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He combined with the bullpen to shut out the Royals, 1–0, in the third and final game of the ALCS.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Though Morris was the ace, the Tigers' MVP was Willie Hernández.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Tigers traded John Wockenfuss and Glenn Wilson to the Phillies in March for Hernández and Dave Bergman.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Hernández appeared in a team record 80 games for the 1984 Tigers and was virtually untouchable.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He allowed 96 hits and only 6 home runs while throwing an incredible 140+1⁄3 innings out of the bullpen, and finished the season with a stellar 1.92 ERA.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] His Adjusted ERA+ of 204 is one of the highest in Detroit Tigers history.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] With 32 saves and 68 games finished, Hernandez won the Cy Young Award and was voted the American League's Most Valuable Player.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] His 32 saves came in 33 opportunities, his only blown save coming in late September after the Tigers had already secured the AL East Division title.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Hernandez saved three post-season games, including the series-clinching games in both the ALCS and World Series.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The popular Aurelio López, known as "Señor Smoke", also had a strong season as the Tigers #2 relief pitcher.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Lopez finished the season with 41 games finished, a record of 10–1 and a 2.94 ERA.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He also saved 14 games while pitching 137+2⁄3 innings.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Lopez earned a win in Game 2 of the ALCS, tossing three scoreless innings as the Tigers won in 11 innings.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Almost lost in the World Series Game 5 hitting heroics of Kirk Gibson was Lopez earning the win with 2+1⁄3 innings of scoreless relief, in which he didn't allow a baserunner.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Darrell Evans was the Tigers' big free agent signing before the 1984 season.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Though he had big years in 1985 (40 HRs, 94 RBIs) and 1987 (34 HRs, 99 RBIs), Evans struggled in his first year in the American League, batting .232 with 16 home runs and 63 RBIs.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In the 1984 World Series, Evans went 1-for-15 for an .067 batting average.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The 1984 Tigers had several non-starters who made big contributions to the team's success.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] As a rookie in 1984, Bárbaro Garbey played in 110 games, including appearances at first base, second base, third base, DH, and each of the outfield positions.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Garbey hit .287 and had more RBIs (52) than several starters, including Howard Johnson, Larry Herndon and Dave Bergman.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Ruppert Jones was signed as a free agent one week into the season on April 10, 1984.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He played in 79 games, mostly as a backup in left field.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Jones contributed 12 home runs and 49 RBIs in only 215 at-bats.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] His .516 slugging percentage was tied with Kirk Gibson for the team lead.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Slick-fielding outfielder Rusty Kuntz played in 84 games, primarily as a late-inning defensive replacement, and hit .286 in 140 at-bats—easily the best offensive season of his major league career.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Kuntz's sacrifice fly in the fifth inning of Game 5 of the 1984 World Series broke a 4–4 tie and turned out to be the game-winning and Series-clinching RBI.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Possibly the most popular of the role players was Marty Castillo.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Detroit manager Sparky Anderson is fifth on the all-time list for manager career wins in Major League Baseball, and in 1984 he became the first manager to win the World Series while leading clubs in both leagues.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He previously managed the Cincinnati Reds to the 1975 and 1976 championships, but the Reds inexplicably fired him after a second-place finish in the 1978 season.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Sparky kept a journal during the 1984 season, which was published under the title "Bless You Boys: Diary of the Detroit Tigers' 1984 Season".
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On the day the Tigers clinched the pennant, Sparky wrote in his journal: "I have to be honest.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] I've waited for this day since they fired me in Cincinnati.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] I think they made a big mistake when they did that.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Tigers began the year with an unprecedented start of 35–5.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] For the rest of the season, the team went 69–53 (a .564 winning percentage, which is the pace of a 91 win season).
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] There was a stretch in late July and August where the team lost 12 out of 18.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Tigers finished with a **104–58** record, 15 games ahead of the second place Toronto Blue Jays.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Tigers defeated the Kansas City Royals in the 1984 American League Championship Series, three games to none.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Jack Morris pitched 7 innings and allowed a single run, with Willie Hernández pitching the final 2 innings.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Alan Trammell hit a triple and a home run for 3 RBIs, and Larry Herndon and Lance Parrish also hit home runs for Detroit.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In Game 2, the Tigers won in extra innings 5–3.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Kirk Gibson doubled to drive in Lou Whitaker in the 1st inning and hit a home run in the 3rd.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Dan Petry pitched 7 innings and gave up 2 runs, but a rare blown save by Willie Hernández cost him a victory.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Johnny Grubb hit a double off Dan Quisenberry in the 11th inning to drive in Darrell Evans and Ruppert Jones.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Aurelio López held the Royals scoreless in the 9th, 10th and 11th innings to earn the win.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Game 3 was a pitching duel between Milt Wilcox and Charlie Leibrandt.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Leibrandt pitched a complete game, allowing only 1 run and 3 hits, while Wilcox gave up 2 hits and struck out 8 Royals, with Hernández pitching the 9th inning for the save.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Marty Castillo batted in Chet Lemon for the game's only run, as the Tigers completed a 3-game sweep and advanced to the World Series.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Kirk Gibson was named the Most Valuable Player of the AL Championship Series.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Tigers beat the San Diego Padres in the 1984 World Series, winning the series 4 games to 1.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In Game 1, the Padres led, 2–1, until Larry Herndon hit a 2-out, 2-run home run in the 5th.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Jack Morris did not allow another run in his complete-game effort, and the Tigers won, 3–2.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Padres evened the series in Game 2, on the strength of a Kurt Bevacqua 3-run homer off Dan Petry, as San Diego won its first (and to date only) World Series game.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In Game 3, the Tigers scored 4 runs in the 2nd inning, including 2 on a home run by Marty Castillo, while the San Diego pitchers gave up 11 bases on balls in the first 5 innings, en route to a 5–2 victory for Milt Wilcox.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In Game 4, Alan Trammell hit a pair of 2-run home runs to account for all of Detroit's offense as the Tigers beat Eric Show, 4–2.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Jack Morris got his 2nd Series victory and 2nd complete game.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In Game 5, the Tigers scored 3 runs in the 1st inning, but the Padres rallied to tie it in the 4th inning.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In the 8th, with Detroit leading 5–4, the Tigers got runners to 2nd and 3rd with 1 out.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Padres manager Dick Williams called on Goose Gossage to walk Kirk Gibson and set up a possible double play.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Gossage talked Williams into letting him pitch to Gibson, and Gibson responded with a 3-run blast into the right-field upper deck.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Following the Tigers' victory in Game 5, the celebration by Detroit fans turned violent.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] A well known photograph taken outside Tiger Stadium shows a Tigers "fan" holding a World Series pennant in front of an overturned burning Detroit police car.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The image was printed in newspapers across the country, and became a symbol of Detroit's decline.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p02] Only one of the players named above (Alan Trammell, selected by the Modern Baseball Committee in 2017) has been elected by the Baseball Writers' Association of America to be inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame, and any eligibility to be elected as a player by the BBWAA has expired.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p02] Manager Sparky Anderson was inducted by the Veterans Committee in 2000.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-detroit-tigers-season-p02] In December 2017, the Modern Baseball Era Committee elected to induct Trammell and pitcher Jack Morris in 2018.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1984 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 55th midseason exhibition between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and the National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was played on July 10, 1984, at Candlestick Park in San Francisco, home of the San Francisco Giants of the National League.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in a 3–1 victory for the NL.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The National Leaguers drew first blood in the first off Dave Stieb when Steve Garvey singled to right and went to second on an error by Reggie Jackson.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Garvey then scored on another error by catcher Lance Parrish after Dale Murphy singled.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the second, George Brett tied it with a homer off Charlie Lea, and game MVP Gary Carter quickly gave the NL the lead back with a shot off Dave Stieb.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game would remain 2–1, NL, for five more innings with two noteworthy pitching performances by National League pitchers along the way.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Fernando Valenzuela struck out Dave Winfield, Reggie Jackson, and George Brett in the fourth, and 19-year-old Dwight Gooden fanned Lance Parrish, Chet Lemon, and Alvin Davis in the fifth.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Dale Murphy added a homer in the eighth off Willie Hernández for the final 3-1 margin.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game set a nine-inning All-Star Game record for most strikeouts (21)--which would be broken in 1999.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Huey Lewis and the News sang the United States National Anthem prior to the game, with the Presidio of San Francisco color guard presenting the colors and airplanes from Travis Air Force Base flying over Candlestick Park at the Anthem's conclusion.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The ceremonial first pitch ceremony featured Carl Hubbell and Stu Miller.
[src:alan-trammell/1984-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The honorary captains of the All-Star teams were Hall of Famers Hank Greenberg (AL) and Willie McCovey (NL).
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell won the 1984 World Series championship over his hometown San Diego Padres, earning Series MVP honors.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] His team also won an American League East division championship in 1987.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Although his arm was not overpowering, he had a quick release and made accurate throws, ultimately winning four Gold Glove awards.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell's defense perfectly complemented his double-play partner, Lou Whitaker.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] The two formed the longest continuous double-play combination in major league history, playing 19 seasons together.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] At the plate, Trammell was one of the best-hitting shortstops of his era and won three Silver Slugger awards.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell later served as the Tigers' manager from 2003 through 2005.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He also served as the interim manager for the Arizona Diamondbacks during the final three games of the 2014 season.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2018.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell attended Kearny High School in San Diego, California and played American Legion Baseball.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He was named the 1989 American Legion Graduate of the Year.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] The Detroit Tigers selected him in the second round of the 1976 MLB draft.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Both players became regulars at their positions the following season.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell batted .300 in 1980 as he made the All-Star team for the first time.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In 1983, he batted .319 with 14 home runs, 66 runs batted in and 30 stolen bases.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Having hit .258 in both 1981 and 1982, Trammell won the 1983 MLB Comeback Player of the Year Award in the American League (AL).
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell and Whitaker made a cameo appearance on the television show *Magnum, P.I.*, starring Tom Selleck, during the 1983 season.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Selleck's character was a Tigers fan, as is Selleck himself.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] The Tigers enjoyed a championship-winning season in 1984, when they started the season 35–5 and led the AL wire-to-wire en route to winning the World Series.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Despite a season-long battle with tendinitis in his shoulder that caused him to miss 23 regular season games, Trammell finished fifth in the AL batting race with a .314 mark and ranked eighth in on-base percentage (.382).
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In the AL Championship Series against the Kansas City Royals, he hit .364 with one home run and three RBI.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Finally, in the World Series, he hit .450 (9-for-20) against the San Diego Padres, including a pair of two-run home runs that accounted for all of the Tigers' scoring in a Game 4 victory.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Detroit won the series 4–1, and Trammell was named World Series MVP.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In 1985, after two consecutive years of batting not lower than .314, Trammell was hampered by injuries and posted only a .258 batting average.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He underwent postseason surgery on his left knee and right shoulder.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] The following season, a fully healthy Trammell hit 21 homers and stole 25 bases, becoming only the second player in Detroit history to hit 20+ home runs and steal 20+ bases in the same season.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] (Kirk Gibson was the other, while Curtis Granderson and Robbie Grossman later joined the club.) Trammell also set a career-high with 75 RBI.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In 1987, asked by manager Sparky Anderson to replace the departed Lance Parrish as cleanup hitter, Trammell responded with his best major league season, hitting a career-high 28 home runs to go with a .343 batting average (ranking third in the AL).
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In September, he batted .416 with six homers and 17 RBI and put together an 18-game hitting streak in which he hit .457.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] On the penultimate day of the regular season, he hit a walk-off single against the Toronto Blue Jays to help his team take the AL East division lead, which they clinched the next day.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He became the first Tiger to collect 200 hits and 100 RBI in the same season since Al Kaline did it in 1955.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell also became the first shortstop to hit at least .340 with 20+ home runs and 100+ RBI in a season in big league history.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Despite his efforts, Trammell finished second to Toronto's George Bell in the MVP voting (332–311).
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell followed up with a .311 season in 1988, though a stint on the disabled list limited him to 128 games that year.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Following the 1990 season, in which he hit .304 with 89 RBI in 146 games, Trammell suffered a long string of injuries that reduced his production over his final years.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In 1991, knee and ankle injuries limited Trammell to 101 games.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] During the following season, he played in 29 games before breaking his right ankle and missing the remainder of the 1992 season.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He hit .329 in a resurgent 1993 season but was ineligible to be ranked among the AL batting leaders because he only had 447 plate appearances.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In his final five seasons, Trammell averaged 76 games played after averaging 140 games played the first 13 seasons of his career.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] From 1993 to 1996, Trammell saw less time at shortstop in favor of Travis Fryman and eventually Chris Gomez and Andújar Cedeño.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He instead saw playing time at several positions, including shortstop, third base, second base, left field, center field, and designated hitter.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell retired following the 1996 season.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In his 20-year career, Trammell batted over .300 seven times, ending with a career average of .285 and 185 home runs with 1,003 RBI, 1,231 runs, 2,365 hits, 412 doubles, 55 triples, 236 stolen bases and 850 walks in 2,293 games.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He compiled a .977 fielding percentage at shortstop, his primary position.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In 2001, Trammell was rated as the ninth-best shortstop of all time in "The New Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract", placing him higher than fourteen Hall of Fame shortstops.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In subsequent years, Trammell's candidacy for the Hall of Fame picked up increasing support from the sabermetric community.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] His boost in later years was likely due to voters being more receptive to advanced metrics, such as wins above replacement.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell was on his 15th and final Baseball Writers' Association of America ballot in 2016, failing to earn enough for induction.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell was one of the last candidates to be allowed on the ballot for 15 years after the BBWAA reduced eligibility to ten years, and would next be considered for the Veterans Committee Expansion starting from 2017.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] On December 10, 2017, he was elected to the Hall of Fame by the Modern Baseball Committee alongside teammate Jack Morris.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In 1998, Trammell was elected into the National Polish-American Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Alan Trammell's jersey #3 was retired by the Tigers in a ceremony on August 26, 2018.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] His name and number were added to the brick wall in left-center field at Comerica Park, alongside Charlie Gehringer (#2), Hank Greenberg (#5), Al Kaline (#6), Sparky Anderson (#11), Hal Newhouser (#16), Willie Horton (#23), Ty Cobb (no number) and Jack Morris (#47).
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Jackie Robinson's #42 was retired throughout baseball in 1997.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Double-play mate Lou Whitaker had his #1 retired in 2022, and it now fittingly stands to the right of Trammel's on the outfield wall.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] After his retirement, Trammell coached for Detroit (1999, hitting coach) and the San Diego Padres (2000–2002, first base coach) before becoming a manager.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell was named the manager of a struggling Tigers team on October 9, 2002.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] The team lost 119 games in his first season in 2003, an American League record at the time, before posting a 72–90 record in 2004.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In the 2005 season, however, the team's record regressed slightly, finishing 71–91.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] During Trammell's three years as manager, the Tigers compiled a record of 186–300.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] During the 2003 season, Detroit nearly matched the modern MLB record of 120 losses, set by the expansion New York Mets (40–120) in 1962.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] The Tigers won five of their last six games to avoid the distinction.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] The Mets' major league record and Tigers' American League record for losses was later surpassed by the 2024 Chicago White Sox.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] On October 3, 2005, the Tigers released Trammell after three seasons in which the organization failed to post a winning record.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell was replaced by Jim Leyland on October 4, 2005.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Leyland led Detroit to a 24-game improvement in the regular season, an AL pennant, and a World Series appearance in 2006.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Leyland himself attributed a degree of the success that the Tigers saw in the 2006 postseason to Trammell's efforts in the three years prior.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In October 2006, Trammell returned to Comerica Park for the first time since his firing to participate, along with Sparky Anderson, in pregame festivities prior to Game 2 of the World Series.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell was showered with a lengthy standing ovation from Detroit baseball fans upon taking the field.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] After being replaced by Leyland, Trammell turned down an offer to stay with the Tigers as a special assistant, instead opting to sit out 2006.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] In October 2006, he agreed to join the Chicago Cubs as a bench coach for the 2007 season, a possible precursor to an eventual return to managing a major league club.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] During the four-game suspension of Lou Piniella in 2007, Trammell was acting manager of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell was passed over for the Cubs' managerial position when Lou Piniella retired midway through the 2010 season.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell was named bench coach of the Arizona Diamondbacks in October 2010, joining his former teammate Kirk Gibson.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Gibson had previously been Trammell's bench and hitting coach with the Tigers.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He and Gibson were fired on September 26, 2014, though Trammell stayed on for the final three games of the season to serve as the interim manager.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He had a record of one win and two losses with Arizona.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] On November 3, 2014, it was announced that Trammell would return to Detroit as a special assistant to Tigers' general manager Dave Dombrowski.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] During the 2015 season Trammell served as interim first-base coach when Omar Vizquel temporarily left the team on bereavement leave.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] He wore #4 during this time, as Ian Kinsler was wearing Trammell's familiar #3.
[src:alan-trammell/alan-trammell] Trammell continued to serve as a special assistant to Tigers' GM Al Avila until Avila was dismissed in August 2022, and Avila was replaced as GM by Jeff Greenberg in September 2023, with Trammell maintaining his special assistant role.
